initial_answer:
[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Software engineering is the discipline that uses knowledge of computers and computing to help solve problems, often by designing and implementing solutions using computer systems as tools.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "As software engineers, we use our knowledge of computers and computing to help solve problems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It focuses on using computers as problem-solving tools rather than studying the hardware or theoretical aspects of computing itself.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Instead of investigating hardware design or proving theorems about how algorithms work, a software engineer focuses on the computer as a problem-solving tool.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Software engineering fits into computer science as a practical discipline that applies theories and computer functions to solve problems for customers, using tools and techniques to develop software solutions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The relationship between computer science and software engineering... Computer science provides theories and computer functions, and software engineering uses tools and techniques to solve problems.",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_144_144_44"
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Technical quality focuses on the products and processes, measured with mathematical expressions involving faults, failures, and timing, emphasizing the technical value of software products.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When the focus of quality assessment is on products and processes, we usually measure quality with mathematical expressions involving faults, failures, and timing.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "That is, we look at the technical value of our products, rather than more broadly at their business value, and we make decisions based only on the resulting products' technical quality.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Business quality, on the other hand, is viewed in terms of the products and services being provided by the business in which the software is embedded, reflecting the broader business value rather than just technical aspects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Rarely is the scope broadened to include a business perspective, where quality is viewed in terms of the products and services being provided by the business in which the software is embedded.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Technical quality is important because it provides measurable indicators of software faults and failures, which are critical for developers and maintainers to ensure the software functions correctly and efficiently.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Practitioners often look at numbers and types of faults for evidence of a product's quality (or lack of it). For example, developers track the number of faults found in requirements, design, and code inspections and use them as indicators of the likely quality of the final product.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Business quality is important because it aligns software quality with business goals, ensuring that the software delivers value to the business, such as customer satisfaction, competitive advantage, and financial returns.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Our success criteria must make sense not only for software projects and processes, but also for the more general business practices they support.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Decreased time to market as well as improved product quality are perceived as offering business value, too.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Failures in software occur when the software does not do what the requirements describe, which can be due to faults in specification, design, or code.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "What do we mean when we say that our software has failed? Usually,we mean that the software does not do what the requirements describe.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Examples of software failures include a system responding to an unauthorized user due to faults in specification, design, or code.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, the specification may state that the system must respond to a particular query only when the user is authorized to see the data. If the program responds to an unauthorized user, we say that the system has failed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Examples of failures in safety-critical software systems that affected the quality and safety of the product include:",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Anthes (1997) reported many other instances where software failures led to unacceptable levels of harm.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "An intravenous medication pump ran dry and injected air into a patient.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An intravenous medication pump ran dry and injected air into a patient.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "A monitor failed to sound an alarm when a patient's heart stopped beating.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A monitor failed to sound an alarm when a patient's heart stopped beating.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "A respirator delivered 'unscheduled breaths' to a patient.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A respirator delivered 'unscheduled breaths' to a patient.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "A digital display combined the name of one patient with medical data from another patient.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A digital display combined the name of one patient with medical data from another patient.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "These failures affected the quality of the software product by causing harm or injury, demonstrating that software faults in safety-critical systems can have severe consequences and reduce the reliability and safety of the product.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Such systems are called safety-critical , since the consequences of their failure are so severe.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Anthes (1997) reported many other instances where software failures led to unacceptable levels of harm.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Failures in software can be caused by various types of faults and errors, which can be identified and classified to understand their origins and nature.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "No matter how capably we write programs, it is clear from the variety of possible faults that we should check to ensure that our components are coded correctly.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Common faults that cause failures include algorithmic faults, syntax faults, and computation and precision faults.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An algorithmic fault occurs when a component's algorithm or logic does not produce the proper output for a given input because something is wrong with the processing steps.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When checking for algorithmic faults, we may also look for syntax faults.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Computation and precision faults occur when a formula's implementation is wrong or does not compute the result to the required number of decimal places.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Examples of faults that can cause failures include",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Typical algorithmic faults include When checking for algorithmic faults, we may also look for syntax faults.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Branching too soon or too late",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- branching too soon - branching too late",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Testing for the wrong condition",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- testing for the wrong condition",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Forgetting to initialize variables or set loop invariants",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- forgetting to initialize variables or set loop invariants",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Forgetting to test for particular conditions such as division by zero",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- forgetting to test for a particular condition (e.g., when division by zero might occur)",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Comparing variables of inappropriate data types",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- comparing variables of inappropriate data types",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, faults can arise from misunderstandings during earlier development activities, and these faults are different from hardware faults as software faults do not result from physical wear or external factors.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "It is entirely possible that a fault in the software can result from a misunderstanding during an earlier development activity.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "It is important to remember that software faults are different from hardware faults.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To document faults and failures effectively, fault report forms should include detailed information such as location, timing, symptom, end-result, mechanism, cause, severity, and cost.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In general, a fault report form should address our list of questions with this kind of detailed information (Fenton and Pfleeger 1997): Location, Timing, Symptom, End-result, Mechanism, Cause, Severity, Cost.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Older issues of software magazines such as IEEE Software and Communications of the ACM from the 1970s and 1980s focused on foundational topics like testing philosophy, specific testing techniques, and maintenance challenges.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Myers (1979) is the classic text, describing the philosophy of testing as well as several specific techniques.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The IEEE Software 's January 1990 issue had maintenance, reverse engineering, and design recovery as its theme; the January 1995 issue focused on legacy systems, and the January 1993 issue has a good article by Wilde, Matthews, and Huitt on the special maintenance problems of object-oriented systems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, more recent issues of these magazines address advanced and specialized topics such as test-driven development, software dependability, usability testing, and testing in object-oriented systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The May 2007 issue addressed test-driven development.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Software dependability and safety-critical systems are receiving more and more attention, and there are many good articles and books about the key issues, including Leveson (1996, 1997).",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Usability tests and more general usability issues are covered in depth in Hix and Hartson (1993).",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The September 1994 issue of Communications of the ACM discusses special considerations in testing object-oriented systems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Older issues also emphasized general testing theory and maintenance, while recent issues include more focus on tools, automation, and evolving software engineering practices.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The proceedings of the annual International Conference on Software Engineering usually has good papers on the latest in testing theory.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "There are several standards related to software requirements. The U.S. Department of Defense has produced MilStd-498, Data Item Description for Software Requirements Specifications (SRS). The IEEE has produced IEEE Std 830-1998, which is a set of recommended practices and standards for formulating and structuring requirements specifications.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "There are several tools that support requirements capture and traceability. DOORS/ERS (Telelogic), Analyst Pro (Goda Software), and RequisitePro (IBM Rational) are popular tools for managing requirements, tracing requirements in downstream artifacts, tracking changes, and assessing the impact of changes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A process to get ready for class or work in the morning can be described as a sequence of activities that transform the initial state (e.g., waking up) into the final state (being ready).",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The process can be modeled using a transition diagram similar to the Lai notation example shown for a car, where states represent conditions and arrows represent actions or events that cause transitions between states.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "[FIGURE 2.12 Transition diagram for a car (Lai 1991).]",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_644_644_165"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, the states could be: 'Asleep', 'Woke Up', 'Dressed', and 'Ready'. The transitions could be actions like 'Wake up', 'Get dressed', and 'Prepare materials'.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A simple transition diagram for the morning preparation process might look like this:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "States and transitions in the morning preparation process",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "'Asleep' --(Wake up)--> 'Woke Up'",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "'Woke Up' --(Get dressed)--> 'Dressed'",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "'Dressed' --(Prepare materials)--> 'Ready'",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This diagram captures the process as a series of states and transitions, similar to the Lai transition diagram example.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "[FIGURE 2.12 Transition diagram for a car (Lai 1991).]",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_644_644_165"
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The waterfall model is a software development life-cycle model that prescribes a sequence of activities including unit testing, integration testing, system testing, system delivery, and maintenance.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The waterfall model has been used to prescribe software development activities in a variety of contexts.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- unit testing - integration testing - system testing - system delivery - maintenance",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The inputs to these activities include code modules and requirements, and the outputs are tested code and integrated systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "'unit and integration testing' in the waterfall ends with the milestone 'code modules written, tested, and integrated'; the intermediate deliverable is a copy of the tested code.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This model is well suited for projects with clear, fixed requirements and where a structured approach is needed, such as government contracts.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The waterfall model has been used to prescribe software development activities in a variety of contexts. For example, it was the basis for software development deliverables in U.S. Department of Defense contracts for many years.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "It is inappropriate for projects where requirements are expected to change frequently or are not well understood, because it is rigid and does not easily accommodate feedback loops.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Many other, more complex models are really just embellishments of the waterfall, incorporating feedback loops and extra activities.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The phased development model involves building software in increments or iterations, where each increment delivers a part of the system that can be used and evaluated.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Phased Development: Increments and Iterations",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_570_570_145"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The main activities include building releases and using releases, with inputs being the previous release and outputs being the next release and production systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_570_570_145"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This model is well suited for projects where requirements evolve over time and early delivery of partial functionality is beneficial.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "It is less appropriate for projects requiring a fully defined system upfront or where partial systems cannot be used independently.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Software development processes generally involve a sequence of activities with constraints, resources, and outputs, and can be described as a life cycle from conception to maintenance.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When the process involves the building of some product, we sometimes refer to the process as a life cycle . Thus, the software development process is sometimes called the software life cycle , because it describes the life of a software product from its conception to its implementation, delivery, use, and maintenance.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Each activity in the process has inputs, outputs, constraints, and resources, and the process is organized in a sequence with entry and exit criteria.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Each process activity has entry and exit criteria, so that we know when the activity begins and ends.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The activities are organized in a sequence, so that it is clear when one activity is performed relative to the other activities.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Static modeling provides a view of the system as it is working today, showing the relationships among roles, activities, and artifacts at a given time.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The static view tells us how the system is working today",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The process model shows the relationships among the roles, activities, and artifacts, and state tables show information about the completeness of each artifact at a given time.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Dynamic modeling, on the other hand, shows how the system is changing into what it will eventually become and enables simulation of the process to observe resource flow and effects of changes before actual resources are expended.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The dynamic view shows us how the system is changing into what it will eventually become.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A desirable property of a process model is the ability to enact the process, so that we can watch what happens to resources and artifacts as activities occur.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "This dynamic process view enables us to simulate the process and make changes before the resources are actually expended.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Static modeling is useful for organizing and depicting process information, such as user requirements and the relationships among process elements, while dynamic modeling is useful for simulating process behavior, testing process choices, and understanding how changes affect effort, schedule, and productivity.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Lai's notation is a good example of how multiple structures and strategies can be used to capture a great deal of information about the software development process.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We want to describe a model of the process and then watch as software shows us how resources flow through activities to become outputs.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can use a dynamic process model to help us decide how many testers we need or when we must initiate testing in order to finish on schedule.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Abdel-Hamid and Madnick have applied system dynamics to software development, enabling project managers to 'test out' their process choices before imposing them on developers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Curtis, Kellner, and Over (1992) identified five desirable properties of process modeling tools and techniques: facilitating human understanding and communication, supporting process improvement, supporting process management, providing automated guidance in performing the process, and supporting automated process execution.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Curtis, Kellner, and Over (1992) have identified five categories of desirable properties: - Facilitates human understanding and communication... - Supports process improvement... - Supports process management... - Provides automated guidance in performing the process... - Supports automated process execution.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Evaluating a process modeling tool or technique using these properties can be illustrated by considering process programming, as proposed by Osterweil (1987).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In the mid-1980s, Osterweil (1987) proposed that software engineering processes be specified using algorithmic descriptions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Process programming aims to automate the process by writing a program to describe and enact the process, which aligns with the property of supporting automated process execution and providing automated guidance.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The goal of process programming is to eliminate uncertainty, both by having enough understanding to write software to capture its essence, and by turning the process into a deterministic solution to the problem. Were process programming possible, we could have management visibility into all process activities, automate all activities, and coordinate and change all activities with ease.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, Curtis, Krasner, Shen, and Iscoe (1987) point out that process programming does not fully support facilitating human understanding and communication or supporting process management due to the inherent variability in human tasks and the need for shared mental models among team members.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Curtis, Krasner, Shen, and Iscoe (1987) point out that Osterweil's analogy to computer programming does not capture the inherent variability of the underlying development process... The coordination of a web of creative intellectual tasks does not appear to be improved greatly by current implementations of process programming, because the most important source of coordination is to ensure that all of the interacting agents share the same mental model of how the system should operate.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Therefore, while process programming supports automated process execution and guidance, it is limited in supporting human understanding, communication, and process management, especially in situations with high variability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Curtis and his colleagues suggest that process programming be restricted only to those situations with minimal variability.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Prescriptive process models are prescriptions for the way software development should progress, providing frameworks and methods to help decision-makers improve their performance in problem-finding and problem-solving given real constraints.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "prescriptive theories provide frameworks and methods to help decision-makers improve their performance in problem-finding and problem-solving, given real constraints.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Some are prescriptions for the way software development should progress",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Descriptive process models provide evidence about how decisions are actually made and describe the way software development is done in actuality.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Descriptive theories provide evidence about how decisions are actually made",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "others are descriptions of the way software development is done in actuality",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The purpose of prescriptive models is to guide and improve the software development process by providing a recommended approach, while descriptive models help teams understand the gap between what should be and what is by describing actual practices.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
