[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A degree process (bachelor's, master's, or PhD) can be described as a work breakdown structure by dividing it into discrete activities such as course enrollment, attending classes, completing assignments, passing exams, conducting research (for master's and PhD), writing a thesis or dissertation, and graduation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Analysis of this kind is sometimes described as generating a work breakdown structure for a given project, because it depicts the project as a set of discrete pieces of work.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "An activity graph for the degree process would represent milestones such as enrollment, course completion, thesis submission, and graduation as nodes, with activities like attending classes, passing exams, and research as edges connecting these milestones.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can illustrate the relationships among activities by using these parameters. In particular, we can draw an activity graph to depict the dependencies; the nodes of the graph are the project milestones, and the lines linking the nodes represent the activities involved.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The critical path in this activity graph is the sequence of activities that determines the minimum time to complete the degree, such as enrollment, completing required courses, passing exams, completing thesis or dissertation, and graduation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The chart helps the project manager to understand which activities can be performed concurrently, and also to see which items are on the critical path.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One popular organizational structure for software development and maintenance projects is the chief programmer team, where one person is totally responsible for a system's design and development.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One popular organizational structure is the chief programmer team, first used at IBM (Baker 1972).On a chief programmer team , one person is totally responsible for a system's design and development.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "All other team members report to the chief programmer, who has the final say on every decision.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "All other team members report to the chief programmer, who has the final say on every decision.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The chief programmer supervises all others, designs all programs, and assigns the code development to the other team members.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The chief programmer supervises all others, designs all programs, and assigns the code development to the other team members.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Assisting the chief is an understudy who substitutes when necessary, and a librarian maintains project documentation, compiles and links code, and performs preliminary testing.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Assisting the chief is an understudy, whose principal job is substituting for the chief programmer when necessary. A librarian assists the team, responsible for maintaining all project documentation. The librarian also compiles and links the code, and performs preliminary testing of all modules submitted to the library.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Regarding work styles of co-workers, there are four basic types based on communication and decision-making styles: rational extroverts, rational introverts, intuitive extroverts, and intuitive introverts.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can define four basic work styles, corresponding to the four quadrants of the graph. The rational extroverts tend to assert their ideas and not let 'gut feeling' affect their decision making. The rational introverts also avoid emotional decisions, but they are willing to take time to consider all possible courses of action.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "For example, Kai is a rational extrovert who prioritizes efficiency and makes quick decisions based on results.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Kai, a rational extrovert, judges her colleagues by the results they produce. When making a decision, her top priority is efficiency. Thus, she wants to know only the bottom line. She examines her options and their probable effects, but she does not need to see documents or hear explanations supporting each option.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Marcel is a rational introvert who values thoroughness and accuracy, preferring to gather all relevant information before making decisions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Marcel, a rational introvert, is very different from his colleague Kai. He judges his peers by how busy they are, and he has little tolerance for those who appear not to be working hard all the time. He is a good worker, admired for the energy he devotes to his work. His reputation as a good worker is very important to him, and he prides himself on being accurate and thorough. He does not like to make decisions without complete information.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "David is an intuitive extrovert who trusts his feelings and professional judgment, enjoys sharing ideas, and prefers a highly interactive work environment.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "David, an intuitive extrovert. Whereas Marcel will not make a decision without complete knowledge of the situation, David prefers to follow his feelings. Often, he will trust his intuition about a problem, basing his decision on professional judgment rather than a slow, careful analysis of the information at hand. Since he is assertive, David tends to tell the others on his project about his new ideas. He is creative, and he enjoys when others recognize his ideas. David likes to work in an environment where there is a great deal of interaction among the staff members.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The advantages of the chief programmer team structure include clear responsibility and decision-making authority, allowing programmers to focus on programming while the librarian handles documentation and preliminary testing.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "This division of labor allows the programmers to focus on what they do best: programming.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Potential problems with the structure could arise if team members are not flexible enough to interact effectively with others who have different work styles, as effective communication and coordination are essential for project success.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Good project managers are aware of these issues, and they seek team members who are flexible enough to interact with all players, regardless of work style.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Two techniques for making a prediction for effort are expert judgment and machine-learning methods.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Many effort-estimation methods rely on expert judgment.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "some researchers are looking to machine learning for assistance in producing good estimates.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Expert judgment is often used early in the development process to make an educated guess about the effort needed to build an entire system or its subsystems, based on a manager's experience with similar projects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In its simplest form, such an estimate makes an educated guess about the effort needed to build an entire system or its subsystems.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Some are informal techniques, based on a manager's experience with similar projects.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The prediction using expert judgment can be repeated and refined using techniques such as the Delphi technique, where experts make individual predictions secretly, then revise their estimates after seeing the group's average until no expert wants to revise further.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Delphi technique makes use of expert judgment in a different way. Experts are asked to make individual predictions secretly, based on their expertise and using whatever process they choose. Then, the average estimate is calculated and presented to the group. Each expert has the opportunity to revise his or her estimate, if desired. The process is repeated until no expert wants to revise.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Machine-learning methods, such as neural networks, are developed by training them with data from past projects and can be used to predict effort during the development process by identifying patterns in historical data.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Neural networks are developed by 'training' them with data from past projects. Relevant data are supplied to the network, and the network uses forward and backward algorithms to 'learn' by identifying patterns in the data.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The prediction using machine-learning methods can be updated as more data become available, allowing the model to improve its accuracy over time.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Neural networks are developed by 'training' them with data from past projects.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Two values that can be calculated from the estimate, E, and the actual value, A, to help determine the accuracy of the estimating process are the acceptance range and bias.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In a stochastic model, we allow for a window of error around the actual value, and the width of the window can vary. Prediction systems for software cost estimation, effort estimation, schedule estimation, and reliability have large margins of error; we say that they are very stochastic. For example, we may find that, under certain circumstances, our organization's reliability prediction is accurate to within 20%; that is, the predicted time to next failure will be within 20% of the actual time. We describe this window by using an acceptance range: a statement of the maximum difference between prediction and actual value.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We deal with bias by comparing how often the observed times of failure are less than the predicted ones. That is, when a given model predicts that the next failure will occur at a particular time, we measure the actual time of next failure and compare the two. Suppose the clock starts at 0 and the first failure occurs at time The time to the next failure is and we continue to record interfailure times until we have observed n software failures, with interfailure times through We compare these times with the predictions (from the model) of through Then, we count the number of times that is less than if this number is significantly less than n /2, then we are likely to have bias in our predictions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The acceptance range is defined as the maximum difference allowed between the predicted value and the actual value for the prediction to be considered accurate. For example, an acceptance range of 20% means the predicted time to next failure should be within 20% of the actual time. This range is set in advance and determines whether the prediction is acceptable based on how close E is to A.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We describe this window by using an acceptance range: a statement of the maximum difference between prediction and actual value. Thus, 20% is the model's acceptance range.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We must always state in advance what range is acceptable before using a prediction system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Bias is measured by comparing how often the actual observed values are less than the predicted values. If the number of times the actual value is less than the predicted value is significantly less than half the total observations, the predictions are biased. For example, if the predicted medians are consistently larger than the actual times, the model is too optimistic. Conversely, if the predicted values are consistently smaller, the model is pessimistic. Detecting bias helps determine if the prediction model systematically overestimates or underestimates the actual values.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We deal with bias by comparing how often the observed times of failure are less than the predicted ones. That is, when a given model predicts that the next failure will occur at a particular time, we measure the actual time of next failure and compare the two. ... Then, we count the number of times that is less than if this number is significantly less than n /2, then we are likely to have bias in our predictions.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, in Figure 13.1, 66 of the 100 observations used with the Jelinski-Moranda model are smaller than the predicted median time to next failure. That is, the predicted medians are too large, so we say that the Jelinski-Moranda model is too optimistic on this dataset.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One size measure in object-oriented (OO) systems is the number of scenario scripts (NSS) in use cases, which counts the number of tasks performed by the system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Lorenz and Kidd count the number of scenario scripts (NSS) in the use cases. They report that this measure is correlated with application size and number of test cases.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The advantage of NSS is that it can be used early in development to feed estimation models for predicting project effort or duration and to help prepare and allocate resources for testing.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "As a size measure, it can feed an estimation model for predicting project effort or duration. As a test case estimate, it helps the test team prepare test cases and allocate resources for future testing activities.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "However, NSS primarily reflects the number of use case tasks and may not capture detailed design or code complexity.",
        "citations": [],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Another size measure is the number of key classes (domain classes) in the system, which evaluates high-level design and suggests the effort needed to build the system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Lorenz and Kidd count the number of key classes (i.e., domain classes) in the system. This measure is intended to evaluate high-level design, suggesting how much effort is needed to build the system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This measure can be taken early during requirements capture and is more concrete and accurate than traditional requirements-counting schemes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The number of use case scripts and number of key classes can be measured very early, during requirements capture. This type of size measurement is typically more concrete and accurate than the requirements-counting schemes used in more traditional development.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "However, it may not reflect the detailed structure or complexity within classes or the system's inheritance hierarchy.",
        "citations": [],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Yes, it is appropriate to specify that the system should not do what it is not intended to do.",
        "citations": [
