[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "There are different consumers of software requirements, each using the requirements for distinct purposes and requiring the requirements to be documented accordingly.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In the end, the requirements are used by many different people and for different purposes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "The different consumers of software requirements and their uses are:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Requirements analysts and their clients use requirements to explain their understanding of how the system should behave.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Requirements analysts and their clients use requirements to explain their understanding of how the system should behave.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Designers treat requirements as constraints on what would be considered an acceptable solution.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Designers treat requirements as constraints on what would be considered an acceptable solution.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "The test team derives from the requirements a suite of acceptance tests, which will be used to demonstrate to the customer that the system being delivered is indeed what was ordered.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The test team derives from the requirements a suite of acceptance tests , which will be used to demonstrate to the customer that the system being delivered is indeed what was ordered.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "The maintenance team uses the requirements to help ensure that system enhancements (repairs and new features) do not interfere with the system's original intent.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The maintenance team uses the requirements to help ensure that system enhancements (repairs and new features) do not interfere with the system's original intent.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To make the requirements useful for these different consumers, the documentation should be tailored accordingly.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Sometimes a single document can serve all of these needs, leading to a common understanding among customers, requirements analysts, and developers. But often two documents are needed: a requirements definition that is aimed at a business audience, such as clients, customers, and users, and a requirements specification that is aimed at a technical audience, such as designers, testers, and project managers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Specifically:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "The requirements definition is aimed at a business audience (clients, customers, users) and expresses requirements by describing the entities in the environment and the desired constraints, serving as a contract describing what functionality the developer promises to deliver.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "a requirements definition that is aimed at a business audience, such as clients, customers, and users",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A requirements definition is a complete listing of everything the customer wants to achieve. The document expresses requirements by describing the entities in the environment in which the proposed system will be installed, and by describing the desired constraints on, monitoring of, or transformations of those entities. The purpose of the proposed system is to realize these requirements (Zave and Jackson 1997). Thus, the requirements are written entirely in terms of the environment, describing how the environment will be affected by the proposed system.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The requirements definition is typically written jointly by the client and the requirements analyst, and it represents a contract describing what functionality the developer promises to deliver to the client.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "The requirements specification is aimed at a technical audience (designers, testers, project managers) and restates the requirements as a specification of how the proposed system shall behave, focusing on environmental entities accessible to the system via its interface.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "a requirements specification that is aimed at a technical audience, such as designers, testers, and project managers.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The requirements specification restates the requirements as a specification of how the proposed system shall behave. The specification also is written entirely in terms of the environment, except that it refers solely to environmental entities that are accessible to the system via its interface.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, the requirements definition helps business stakeholders understand what the system will achieve in the environment, while the requirements specification helps technical stakeholders understand how the system will behave and interact with the environment.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One source of problems in the requirements phase can be the relationship between system developers and their customers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One source of problems in the requirements phase can be the relationship between system developers and their customers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Negative stereotypes customers may hold about developers include misunderstandings about how certain functions will produce results, unrealistic expectations about data formats or system goals, and doubts about the feasibility of meeting reliability or availability targets.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "validation may reveal that there is a great misunderstanding about the way in which a certain function will produce results. The customers may require data to be reported in miles, whereas the users want the data in kilometers. The customers may set a reliability or availability goal that developers deem impossible to meet.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To minimize the impact of these negative stereotypes, as a developer you can engage in thorough validation and verification activities, including reviewing the information flow and proposed functions with customer representatives to confirm accuracy and realism, assessing and documenting risks, discussing and comparing alternatives, and resolving conflicts before design begins.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The customer's representatives review the information flow and the proposed functions, to confirm that they accurately reflect the customer's needs and intentions. Our representatives review the proposed functions and constraints, to confirm that they are realistic and within our development abilities. If any risk is involved in the development or in the actual functioning of the system, we can assess and document this risk, discuss and compare alternatives, and come to some agreement on the approaches to be used. These conflicts need to be resolved before design can begin.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, constructing simulations or prototypes to explore feasibility constraints and working collaboratively with the customer to agree on acceptable requirements can help resolve misunderstandings and build trust.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To resolve a conflict, the developers may need to construct simulations or prototypes to explore feasibility constraints and then work with the customer to agree on an acceptable requirement.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Robertsons' requirements definition template, available at http://www.systemsguild.com, is a comprehensive tool designed to assist software developers in eliciting, documenting, and validating requirements effectively.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A comprehensive requirements-definition template developed by James and Suzanne Robertson can be found at the Web site of the Atlantic Systems Guild: http:// www.systemsguild.com.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The template is particularly helpful during the requirements elicitation and documentation phases, as it provides a structured format to capture requirements in the customer's terms, ensuring clarity and completeness.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The requirements definition is a record of the requirements expressed in the customer's terms.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To use the template for validating requirements, the development team must engage in activities such as eliciting requirements from customers and users, documenting them clearly, and reviewing the requirements collaboratively with stakeholders including designers, testers, and documentation writers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Your development team must work together to elicit, understand, and document requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Finally, you must work as a team to review the requirements definition and specification documents, and to update those documents as the requirements change and grow during the development and maintenance processes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The developer applying the template should possess skills in communication and collaboration to work effectively with customers, users, designers, testers, and documentation writers. They should also be capable of linking and controlling requirements to manage changes and ensure consistency.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Your team must also pay attention to measurements that reflect requirements quality.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Because the disparate requirements will be integrated into a comprehensive whole, requirements must be written in a way that allows them to be linked and controlled.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Using the template helps uncover errors and faults such as incomplete, inconsistent, or unclear requirements by providing a structured approach to documenting and reviewing requirements, which supports early detection and correction of issues.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, a change to one requirement may affect other, related requirements, and the methods and tools must support the changes to ensure that errors are caught early and quickly.",
