[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Module “InventorySearchByID” is likely to have a high degree of cohesion because it performs a single, well-defined function: searching the records in inventory for matching ID numbers and returning the results.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Our ideal is functional cohesion , where two conditions hold: all elements essential to a single function are contained in one module, and all of that module's elements are essential to the performance of that function. A functionally cohesive module performs only the function for which it is designed, and nothing else.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Module “ProcessPurchase” is likely to have a low degree of cohesion because it serves multiple purposes: removing the purchased product from inventory, printing a receipt, and updating the log. This means the module's elements may need to evolve in different ways or at different rates.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A module that serves multiple purposes is at greater risk of its elements needing to evolve in different ways or at different rates.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Module “FindSet” is likely to have a low degree of cohesion because it combines processing the user's request, determining the matching items, and formatting the list for display. These are different operations that may evolve separately, making the module harder to understand and maintain.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A module has logical cohesion if its parts are related only by the logic structure of its code. As an example, consider a template module or procedure that performs very different operations depending on the values of its parameters. Although the different operations have some cohesion, this cohesion of code structure is weak compared to cohesion of data, function, or purpose. It is likely that the different operations will evolve in different ways over time, and that this evolution, plus the possible addition of new operations, will make the module increasingly difficult to understand and maintain.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A design review is described as \"egoless\" because the criticism and discussion during the review are directed at the process and the product, not at the participants themselves.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The criticism and discussion during the design review are egoless, because comments are directed at the process and the product, not at the participants.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Egoless reviews are necessary because they emphasize that everyone involved is working toward the same goal, which encourages open communication and collaboration among diverse team members.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "It is important to remember that those who participate in the review are investigating the integrity of the design, not of the designers. Thus, the review is valuable in emphasizing to all concerned that we are working toward the same goal. The criticism and discussion during the design review are egoless, because comments are directed at the process and the product, not at the participants. The review process encourages and enhances communication among the diverse members of the team.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Steps that may help achieve egoless reviews include having a moderator who leads the discussion without vested interest, encouraging discussion and maintaining objectivity and balance, and having a recorder who documents the discussion impartially.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The moderator leads the discussion but has no vested interest in the project itself. He or she encourages discussion, acts as an intermediary between opposing viewpoints, keeps the discussion moving, and maintains objectivity and balance in the process. Because it is difficult to take part in the discussion and also record the main points and outcomes, another impartial participant is recruited to serve as recorder. The recorder does not get involved in the issues that arise; his or her sole job is to document what transpires.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Consider a software system such as a billing application used in a service station, where the user interface includes screens for entering billing information.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, the lefthand side of Figure 6.37 shows the paper bill that Manny uses at the Royal Service Station. Now, to automate his billing process, we may suggest a screen like the one on the right-hand side.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A disliked feature might be the complexity or unintuitiveness of the user interface elements, such as buttons or text boxes that were not part of the original user requirements but were added during the design phase.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Notice that this design includes classes for an okay button and a text box. These objects are not likely to have entered our initial conversations with Manny when we derived our use cases from his requirements. They reflect our solution, not his problem.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This problem could have been avoided during the design process by involving the user more closely in iterative prototyping and evaluation of the user interface, ensuring that the interface matches user needs and expectations.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Prototyping means building a small version of a system, usually with limited functionality, that can be used to Often, the prototyping process is iterative: We build a prototype, evaluate it (with user and customer feedback), consider how changes might improve the product or design, and then build another prototype. The iteration ends when we and our customers think we have a satisfactory solution to the problem at hand.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Since the user interface is, in a sense, a bridge between the application domain and the software development team, prototyping can bring to the surface issues and assumptions that may not have been clear using other approaches to requirements analysis.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Changes to the design process that would be necessary include laying out the interaction on paper early, defining scenarios for user tasks, designing a hierarchy of user commands, and integrating user-interface classes into the overall system design with flexibility to accommodate user feedback.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The first step in user-interface design is laying out the interaction on paper. To do this, we determine how paper flows in the existing system; the paper documents may suggest comfortable user interfaces in the automated system.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Let us look more closely at designing a user interface. We must consider several issues: identifying the humans who will interact with the system, defining scenarios for each way that the system can perform a task, designing a hierarchy of user commands, refining the sequence of user interactions with the system, designing relevant classes in the hierarchy to implement the user-interface design decisions, integrating the user-interface classes into the overall system class hierarchy.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "This expansion of classes and hierarchy is another important reason to consider design flexibility as we devise our solution.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A good reference that deals with design patterns in more detail is Gamma et al. (1995), which provides an overview of how to think of systems in terms of design patterns.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Gamma et al. (1995) provide an overview of how to think of systems in terms of design patterns.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Design patterns codify design decisions and best practices for solving particular design problems according to design principles. They are templates for solutions that must be adapted for each use, rather than ready-to-use software libraries.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A design pattern codifies design decisions and best practices for solving a particular design problem according to design principles... they are templates for a solution that must be modified and adapted for each particular use.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One example of a design pattern's usefulness is that it improves a design's modularity by encapsulating particular types of design decisions, such as the choice of algorithm, the type of object instantiated, or the order of traversing a collection of objects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The main goal of design patterns is to improve a design's modularity. In fact, each pattern is designed to encapsulate a particular type of design decision. The decision types vary widely, from the choice of algorithm that implements an operation to the type of object instantiated to the order in which a collection of objects is traversed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Design patterns can be used to make future design changes easier to implement or to enable a program to change its structure or behavior at runtime.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Some design patterns structure a design to make future design changes easier to implement. Other patterns enable a program to change its structure or behavior at runtime.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, design patterns add extra classes, associations, and method calls, which can make the design seem overly complicated and may affect other quality attributes such as performance or ease of development.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Because the patterns add extra classes, associations, and method calls, they sometimes can seem overly complicated. This complexity improves modularity, even at the expense of other quality attributes such as performance or ease of development.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Therefore, design patterns are useful only in situations where the extra flexibility is worth the extra cost required to implement them.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For this reason, the patterns are useful only in situations where the extra flexibility is worth the extra cost required to implement them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Therac-25 accidents highlight several important lessons for software design in safety-critical systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Leveson and Turner (1993) describe the machine, the accidents, and the software issues in great detail, and their article should be required reading for systems and software engineers who design and build safety-critical systems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Key lessons from the Therac-25 accidents include",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Leveson and Turner (1993) describe how the underlying cause of the problems was a timing error that was difficult to reproduce.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Most computer-related accidents result from requirements faults rather than coding faults.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "They point out that most computer-related accidents result from requirements faults, not from coding faults.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Documentation should be done as development progresses, not afterward.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Documentation should be done as development progresses, not afterward.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Software quality assurance practices should be an integral part of the development process, including early standards and evaluation of intermediate products.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Software quality assurance practices should be an integral part of the development process. These practices should include standards that are set early and used to evaluate intermediate products.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Simple designs are easier to understand, code, and test than complex ones.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- Simple designs are easier to understand, code, and test than complex ones.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Software should be designed to anticipate failures and capture information about them.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- Software should be designed to anticipate failures and capture information about them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "It is not enough to assume that system testing will catch software problems; extensive testing and formal analysis at component and system levels are necessary before hardware integration.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- It is not enough to assume that system testing will catch software problems. Software should be tested extensively, as well as subjected to formal analysis, at the component and system levels before integration with the hardware.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Encapsulation supports reuse by isolating components that were developed separately, allowing programmers to reuse components without change or with some modifications while minimizing the need for extensive retesting of unrelated parts.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "encapsulation isolates components that were developed separately. It is tempting to think that if a programmer reuses some components without change, and reuses others but with some changes, then only the modified code needs to be tested.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Information hiding supports reuse by encapsulating separate design decisions within software units, making the system easier to maintain and allowing reuse of objects with minimal new code.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Information hiding (Parnas 1972) aims to make the software system easier to maintain. It is distinguished by its guidance for decomposing a system: each software unit encapsulates a separate design decision that could be changed in the future.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Maintainers can reuse objects easily, writing only a small amount of new code.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "When deciding whether to reuse a class in a new system, criteria should include whether the class encapsulates changeable design decisions effectively, whether its interface hides aspects likely to change, and whether the class can be integrated without extensive retesting due to inheritance or overriding.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Because we want to encapsulate changeable design decisions, we must ensure that our interfaces do not, themselves, refer to aspects of the design that are likely to change.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "when we add a new subclass or modify an existing subclass, we must retest the methods inherited from each of its ancestor superclasses.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It is useful to have separate phases for system and program design because the system design provides a complete description of the functions and interactions involved, which serves as a basis for generating the designs of the individual programs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The design is then reviewed by the customer.When approved, the overall system design is used to generate the designs of the individual programs involved.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The basis for our discussion is a well-defined description of the software project as a system; the system design includes a complete description of the functions and interactions involved.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This separation ensures that functionality and appearance are determined before coding begins, making it more sensible to consider the details of individual programs only after the system design is approved.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Note that it is not until this step that programs are mentioned. Until functionality and appearance are determined, it often makes no sense to consider coding.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
