        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Using inheritance to create separate subclasses for each service under a general “sale item” class can reduce duplicate code among the subclasses by localizing common code structure in the parent class.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Template Method pattern aims to reduce the amount of duplicate code among subclasses of the same parent class. It is particularly useful when multiple subclasses have similar but not identical implementations of the same method.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This approach allows the parent class to define a template method implementing common steps, while subclasses override specific operations to reflect their unique behaviors.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The abstract class defines a template method that implements the common steps of an operation, and declares abstract primitive operations that represent the variation points. The template method calls the primitive operations at points where its behavior depends on the object being involved. The subclasses override the primitive operations to realize subclass-specific variations of the template method.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, there are arguments against using inheritance in this case, especially if the design results in multiple dependencies among classes, which can increase coupling and make the system harder to maintain.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Although the design advice suggests that we prefer composition over inheritance, the resulting design may have multiple dependencies among classes. This problem occurs whenever a class that depends on a composite class also depends on all of the class's component classes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Such dependencies require knowing the interfaces of all related classes and rechecking implementations whenever any of these classes change.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In such a design, our Bill class accesses and thus depends directly on CustomerAccount, Sale, and Item classes. We must know the interfaces of all of them to invoke the appropriate methods correctly. Worse, we have to recheck our implementation of generateBill() whenever any of these classes is changed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Factors influencing the decision include how much the services share common behavior and attributes, the complexity of their unique behaviors, and the potential for dependencies and coupling in the design.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Template Method pattern is useful when multiple subclasses have similar but not identical implementations of the same method.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Although the design advice suggests that we prefer composition over inheritance, the resulting design may have multiple dependencies among classes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

