[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A stack is a last-in, first-out data structure where elements can only be placed on or removed from the top of the stack.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The allowable operations for a stack are empty, full, push, pop, and top.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The empty operation returns true if there are no elements in the stack, false otherwise.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The full operation returns true if the stack is filled to capacity, false otherwise.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The push operation takes an element as an argument and places the element on top of the stack if the stack is not full; if the stack is full, the push operation returns an error.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The pop operation removes an element from the top of the stack if the stack is not empty; if the stack is empty, the pop operation returns an error, otherwise, the top element is returned.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The top operation returns the element on the top of the stack without removing it if the stack is not empty; it returns an error if the stack is empty.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To implement this stack data structure, use an array to store integer elements with a maximum capacity of 100 elements.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A strategy for finding a reusable component involves creating an inventory of components and forming a matrix with the features of all past and planned projects. Each feature is rated based on whether it has been implemented and is still needed, has been implemented but is no longer needed, or has not been implemented but is still needed. Features that are needed and common to more than one project are targeted for reuse, and some are redesigned to make them more reusable.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Council created an inventory of components and formed a matrix with the features of all past and planned projects. Then, each feature was rated in terms of whether it had been implemented and was still needed, had been implemented but was no longer needed, or had not been implemented but was still needed. Those features that were needed and were common to more than one project were targeted for reuse. In fact, some were redesigned to make them more reusable.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Guidelines for selecting a component for reuse include checking if the component performs the needed function or provides the required data, determining if minor modification is less effort than building from scratch, ensuring the component is well-documented for understanding without verifying line by line, and confirming there is a complete record of the component's test and revision history to ensure it contains no faults.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If you are a consumer for your current project, there are four key characteristics to check about the components you are about to reuse: - Does the component perform the function or provide the data you need? - If minor modification is required, is it less modification than building the component from scratch? - Is the component well-documented, so you can understand it without having to verify its implementation line by line? - Is there a complete record of the component's test and revision history, so you can be certain that it contains no faults?",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additional guidelines to help in the process of selecting a component for reuse include keeping the component interface general and well-defined, including information about any faults found and fixed, using clear naming conventions, documenting data structures and algorithms, and keeping communication and error-handling sections separate and easy to modify.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- Keep the component interface general and well-defined. - Include information about any faults found and fixed. - Use clear naming conventions. - Document the data structures and algorithms. - Keep the communication and error-handling sections separate and easy to modify.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The relationship between design and implementation is that the program code components must directly correspond to the program design components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The most critical standard is the need for a direct correspondence between the program design components and the program code components.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It is important to match the implementation to the design because the design's modularity and characteristics such as low coupling, high cohesion, and well-defined interfaces should be preserved in the code to allow easy tracing of algorithms, functions, interfaces, and data structures from design to code and back again.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Design characteristics, such as low coupling, high cohesion, and well-defined interfaces, should also be program characteristics, so that the algorithms, functions, interfaces, and data structures can be traced easily from design to code and back again.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Matching design and implementation is essential because the system's nature may change over time with enhancements and modifications, and these changes are first made to the high-level design and then traced through lower design levels to the code that must be modified.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "These changes are made first to the high-level design and then are traced through lower design levels to the code that must be modified. Thus, the correspondence between design and code is essential.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Without the links established by matching design and implementation, testing, maintenance, and configuration management are impossible.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In later chapters, we will see that testing, maintenance, and configuration management are impossible without the links established by these standards.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To keep design and implementation consistent, one should use the low-level design as an initial framework and move in several iterations from design to code, preserving the quality design attributes in the code and using documentation within programs and in external documents to explain the code's organization, data, control, function, and design decisions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "using the low-level design as an initial framework, and moving in several iterations from design to code",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "using documentation within your programs and in external documents to explain your code's organization, data, control, and function, as well as your design decisions",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "preserving the quality design attributes in your code",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Reusing code written by someone else is an example of consumer reuse, where you use existing components in subsequent systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By software reuse, we mean the repeated use of any part of a software system... There are two kinds of reuse, as determined by the perspective of the reuser. Producer reuse creates reusable components, and consumer reuse uses them in subsequent systems (Bollinger and Pfleeger 1990).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Problems encountered when reusing code written by someone else include difficulty in understanding and reusing a component written by someone else, lack of documentation on quality assurance and testing, uncertainty about responsibility if the reused component fails or needs updating, and the extra time needed to make a component general enough for reuse.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "It is difficult to document the degree of quality assurance and testing that have been done, so that a potential reuser can feel comfortable about the quality of the component. It is not clear who is responsible if a reused component fails or needs to be updated. It can be costly and time-consuming to understand and reuse a component written by someone else. It may take extra time to make a component general enough to be reusable easily by other developers in the future.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "These problems can be mitigated by establishing a reuse program that includes classifying and cataloguing reusable assets in an automated library system, training software engineers in using the library and recognizing when a structure can be reused, and promoting reuse through management support groups.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The collection of assets was then classified and catalogued in an automated library system. Several groups were created to maintain the library, promote reuse, and support reusers: - a management support group to provide initiatives, funding, and policies for reuse",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Software engineers are trained and tested in using the library and in recognizing when a structure can be reused to build a new application. Reuse is then compulsory.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, verifying that a reused module performs its required function in an acceptable way, ensuring it is failure-free, and confirming thorough testing can help increase confidence in reused components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An important issue in black-box reuse is our ability to verify that a reused module performs its required function in an acceptable way. If the component is code, we want to be sure it is failure-free; if it is a test set, we want to be sure it thoroughly exercises the function for which it is intended.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "When writing code in a team environment, it is essential to follow coding standards and procedures to ensure clarity, maintainability, and effective collaboration.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Even when writing the code itself, many people are usually involved, and a great deal of cooperation and coordination is required. Thus, it is very important for others to be able to understand not only what you have written, but also why you have written it and how it fits in with their work.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Below is a set of coding standards for Python, chosen to promote readability, reusability, and ease of maintenance, aligned with the guidelines from the chapter:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Coding Standards for Python include",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Follow PEP 8 style guidelines for code formatting to ensure consistency in indentation, naming conventions, and line length.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Many companies insist that their code conform to style, format, and content standards, so that the code and associated documentation are clear to everyone who reads them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Use clear and descriptive names for variables, functions, and classes to make the code self-explanatory.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "It is very important for others to be able to understand not only what you have written, but also why you have written it and how it fits in with their work.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Document your code thoroughly with comments and docstrings explaining the purpose, inputs, outputs, and any design decisions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Some of the procedures involve methods of documenting your code so that it is clear and easy to follow. Such documentation allows you to leave and return to your work without losing track of what you had been doing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Use modular design and information hiding to reveal only essential information about components, facilitating reuse and testing.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Your use of information hiding allows you to reveal only the essential information about your components so that your colleagues can invoke them or reuse them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Incorporate a systemwide error-handling strategy to manage exceptions and maintain program stability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "incorporating a systemwide error-handling strategy",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Write reusable code by designing functions and classes that can be used in future projects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "writing your code to make it reusable on future projects",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Use consistent naming conventions and formatting to enhance communication among team members.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Your use of standards enhances communication among team members.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "These standards are included because they help organize thoughts, avoid mistakes, and make the code easier to understand, maintain, and reuse by others in the team, which is critical in a collaborative software development environment.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Standards and procedures can help you to organize your thoughts and avoid mistakes. Some of the procedures involve methods of documenting your code so that it is clear and easy to follow.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Your use of standards enhances communication among team members.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "When examining faults from code, each fault should be identified by its type according to Section 8.1, Types of Faults, and classified using a defect classification scheme such as IBM's or Hewlett-Packard's.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "After coding the program components, we usually examine the code to spot faults and eliminate them right away. When no obvious faults exist, we then test our program to see if we can isolate more faults by creating conditions where the code does not react as planned.Thus, it is important to know what kind of faults we are seeking.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Fault classifications, such as IBM's and Hewlett-Packard's (see Sidebar 8.1), help improve the entire development process by telling us which types of faults are found in which development activities.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Types of faults include algorithmic faults, syntax faults, computation and precision faults, and standards and procedure faults.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An algorithmic fault occurs when a component's algorithm or logic does not produce the proper output for a given input because something is wrong with the processing steps. ... When checking for algorithmic faults, we may also look for syntax faults ... Computation and precision faults occur when a formula's implementation is wrong or does not compute the result to the required number of decimal places. ... Finally, the code should be reviewed to confirm that organizational standards and procedures have been followed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "IBM's defect classification, called orthogonal defect classification, categorizes faults to identify which parts of the development process need attention. Faults are classified as faults of omission (missing key aspects) or faults of commission (incorrect aspects).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Chillarege et al. (1992) at IBM have developed an approach to fault tracking called orthogonal defect classification, where faults are placed in categories that collectively paint a picture of which parts of the development process need attention because they are responsible for spawning many faults. ... When using the classification, the developers identify not only the type of fault, but also whether it is a fault of omission or commission. A fault of omission is one that results when some key aspect of the code is missing; for example, a fault may occur when a variable is not initialized. A fault of commission is one that is incorrect; for example, the variable is initialized to the wrong value.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Hewlett-Packard's fault classification categorizes faults by origin (where the fault was injected), type of fault, and mode (whether information was missing, unclear, wrong, changed, or could be done a better way).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Grady (1997) describes Hewlett-Packard's approach to fault classification. ... The developers use this model by selecting three descriptors for each fault found: the origin of the fault (i.e., where the fault was injected in a product), the type of fault, and the mode (i.e., whether information was missing, unclear, wrong, changed, or could be done a better way).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Hewlett-Packard fault classification is illustrated in Figure 8.1, showing categories such as Specification/Requirements, Design, Code, Environment/Support, Documentation, and Other, with subcategories and modes of faults.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Figure 8.1 Hewlett-Packard fault classification (Grady 1997).",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_3348_3350_803"
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Difficulties in classifying faults may arise due to overlapping categories, unclear fault origins, or ambiguous fault modes, making it challenging to assign a fault to a single category or mode.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The type of fault that occurred most frequently is related to design, as indicated by the fault profile differences shown in IBM's and Hewlett-Packard's fault classification approaches.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "IBM's use of this concept by showing us that the fault profile for design review is very different from that for code inspection.",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_3352_3353_804"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To reduce the occurrence of design faults, the software development approach should emphasize thorough requirements and design reviews to ensure clarity and correctness of specifications and designs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For this reason, requirements and design reviews are essential to ensuring the quality of the resulting system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This includes addressing misinterpretations and unclear specifications early in the development cycle to prevent faults from propagating into program design and code.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Misinterpretations are common when the system design is translated into lower-level descriptions for program design specifications. Programmers are several levels removed from the initial discussions with customers about system goals and functionality.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Having responsibility for one 'tree' but not the 'forest,' programmers cannot be expected to spot design faults that have been perpetuated through the first steps of the development cycle.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Unit testing is the development activity that exercises each component separately, focusing on testing code components individually to find faults.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Unit testing is the development activity that exercises each component separately",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Integration testing involves putting components together in an organized way to help isolate faults as the combined components are tested together.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "integration testing puts components together in an organized way to help you isolate faults as the combined components are tested together.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The goal of unit testing is to ensure that the code implements the design properly, verifying that programmers wrote code to do what the designers intended.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The objective of unit and integration testing was to ensure that the code implemented the design properly; that is, that the programmers wrote code to do what the designers intended.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The goal of integration testing is to combine components into a working system in a planned and coordinated way so that when a failure occurs, the cause can be identified.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When we are satisfied that individual components are working correctly and meet our objectives, we combine them into a working system. This integration is planned and coordinated so that when a failure occurs, we have some idea of what caused it.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Unit testing should occur during the development phase, focusing on individual components, often using informal walkthroughs or formal inspections, code structure analysis, and performance analysis.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, unit testing may be composed of informal walkthroughs or formal inspections, followed by analyzing the code structure and then analyzing the code's actual performance.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Integration testing should occur after unit testing when individual components are confirmed to work correctly, combining them according to a test strategy that affects integration timing, coding order, cost, and thoroughness.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When we are satisfied that individual components are working correctly and meet our objectives, we combine them into a working system. This integration is planned and coordinated ... This strategy affects not only the integration timing and coding order, but also the cost and thoroughness of the testing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Integration testing can be done using different approaches such as top-down, bottom-up, or a combination of both, and the order of component testing influences the choice of test cases and tools.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The system is again viewed as a hierarchy of components, where each component belongs to a layer of the design. We can begin from the top and work our way down as we test, work from the bottom up, or use a combination of these two approaches.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The order in which components are tested affects our choice of test cases and tools.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Object-oriented testing differs from traditional testing in several key ways related to the nature of objects and inheritance.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Graham (1996a) summarizes the differences between object-oriented and traditional testing in two ways. First, she notes which aspects of object orientation make testing easier and which make it harder.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "The differences include the following aspects",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Graham (1996a) summarizes the differences between object-oriented and traditional testing in two ways.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Inheritance requires additional testing when functions are redefined, have specific behavior in derived classes, or when other functions in the class must remain consistent.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Similarly, inheritance introduces the need for more testing.An inherited function needs additional testing if it is redefined, it has a specific behavior in a derived class, other functions in that class are supposed to be consistent",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Unit testing is generally easier because objects tend to be small and complexity is often pushed toward interfaces, but integration testing is more extensive due to encapsulation and object interactions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "objects tend to be small, and the complexity that might ordinarily reside in the component is often pushed instead toward the interfaces among components. This difference means that unit testing is less difficult, but integration testing must be much more extensive. encapsulation is often considered a positive attribute of object-oriented design, but it also requires more extensive integration testing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Requirements validation and test case generation tools are less effective for object-oriented systems because they are mostly designed for procedural code.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Requirements are likely to be expressed in the requirements document, but there are few tools to support validation of requirements expressed as objects and methods. Likewise, most tools that assist in test case generation are not prepared to handle a model expressed in objects and methods.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Traditional source code metrics like cyclomatic complexity are less useful for object-oriented systems, and code coverage tools are less valuable because complexity arises from object interactions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Most source code measurements are defined for procedural code, not for objects and methods. Traditional metrics such as cyclomatic numbers are of little use when assessing the size and complexity of object-oriented systems. Because it is the interaction of objects that is the source of complexity, code coverage measurements and tools are of less value in object-oriented testing than in traditional testing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "When subclasses override inherited methods, retesting is necessary with possibly different test data, unlike procedural testing where existing test data can often be reused.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When a subclass replaces an inherited method with a locally defined method with the same name, the overriding subclass must be retested, and probably with a different set of test data.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Testing strategies for object-oriented systems often involve testing base classes first, then incrementally updating test histories for subclasses focusing on new or affected attributes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "They first test base classes having no parents; the test strategy is to test each function individually and then test the interactions among functions. Next, they provide an algorithm to update incrementally the test history of the parent class; only attributes that are new or are affected by the inheritance scheme are tested.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Overall, object-oriented testing requires special treatment in planning, requirements analysis and validation, test case generation, source code analysis, and coverage analysis compared to traditional testing.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The diagram in Figure 8.17 is a Kiviat or radar graph that compares the differences between object-oriented and traditional testing. The gray polygon shows that Planning and requirements analysis and validation, test case generation, source code analysis, and coverage analysis require special treatment.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Statement testing requires that every statement in the component is executed at least once in some test.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Statement testing: Every statement in the component is executed at least once in some test.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "All-uses testing requires that the test set includes at least one path from every definition to every use that can be reached by that definition.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "All-uses testing: The test set includes at least one path from every definition to every use that can be reached by that definition.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For the example code in the image, which involves loops and conditional branches, test cases for statement testing would include inputs that ensure each statement (PERFORM A, PERFORM B, PERFORM C, PERFORM D, and the increments of I and J) is executed at least once.",
