]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "System testing differs from unit and integration testing in its objective and focus.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The objective of unit and integration testing was to ensure that the code implemented the design properly; that is, that the programmers wrote code to do what the designers intended.In system testing, we have a very different objective: to ensure that the system does what the customer wants it to do.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Unit and integration testing focus on verifying that individual components and their interactions are implemented correctly according to the design specifications.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Unit and integration testing addresses the correctness of programs, as we shall see in later chapters. The V model suggests that unit and integration testing can also be used to verify the program design.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Unit testing is done in a controlled environment whenever possible, so that the test team can feed a predetermined set of data to the component being tested and observe what output actions and data are produced.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Integration testing is the process of verifying that the system components work together as described in the system and program design specifications.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "System testing, on the other hand, focuses on validating the system's functionality against the customer's requirements, often treating the system as a black box without concern for internal component structure.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "System testing begins with function testing. Whereas previous tests concentrated on components and their interactions, this first step ignores system structure and focuses on functionality.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Function testing is based on the system's functional requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Function testing checks that the integrated system performs its functions as specified in the requirements. It verifies that the system correctly executes its intended operations, such as processing transactions or calculations.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A function test checks that the integrated system performs its functions as specified in the requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Performance testing measures the system's performance against objectives set by the customer, focusing on speed, accuracy, and accessibility of results. It is designed and administered by the test team, often including hardware engineers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "System performance is measured against the performance objectives set by the customer as expressed in the nonfunctional requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Performance testing examines how well the calculation is done; the speed of response to user commands, accuracy of the result, and accessibility of the data are checked against the customer's performance prescriptions.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Performance testing is designed and administered by the test team, and the results are provided to the customer. Because performance testing usually involves hardware as well as software, hardware engineers may be part of the test team.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Acceptance testing is led by the customer to determine if the system meets their needs and expectations. Customers write, conduct, and evaluate these tests, with developers assisting only when technical questions arise.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The purpose of acceptance testing is to enable the customers and users to determine if the system we built really meets their needs and expectations.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Acceptance tests are written, conducted, and evaluated by the customers, with assistance from the developers only when the customer requests an answer to a technical question.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Installation testing involves installing the system at user sites to verify that it works correctly in the actual environment. It includes configuring the system, attaching devices, establishing communications, and running tests to ensure completeness and proper functioning under site conditions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The final round of testing involves installing the system at user sites.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Installation tests require us to work with the customer to determine what tests are needed on-site.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The tests focus on two things: completeness of the installed system and verification of any functional or nonfunctional characteristics that may be affected by site conditions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Verification ensures that we build the system right, whereas validation ensures that we build the right system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To summarize, verification ensures that we build the system right , whereas validation ensures that we build the right system!",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Verification involves checking that one document or artifact conforms to another, such as verifying that code conforms to design, design conforms to requirements specification, and requirements specification conforms to requirements definition.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In verification , we check that one document or artifact conforms to another. Thus, we verify that our code conforms to our design,and that our design conforms to our requirements specification;at the requirements level, we verify that our requirements specification conforms to the requirements definition.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Validation involves checking that the requirements definition accurately reflects the customer's and all stakeholders' needs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In requirements validation , we check that our requirements definition accurately reflects the customer's-actually, all of the stakeholders'needs.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Types of testing that address verification include unit and integration testing, system testing, and acceptance testing, which verify design and code against requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "FIGURE 2.4 The V model.",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_543_543_138"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Validation is addressed during requirements analysis and validation phases, where the requirements are validated with the customer to ensure they meet the needs and intentions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Remember that the requirements documents serve both as a contract between us and the  customer, detailing  what  we  are  to  deliver, and  as guidelines  for  the  designers, detailing what they are to build. Thus, before the requirements can be turned over to the  designers, we  and  our  customers  must  be  absolutely  sure  that  each  knows  the other's intent, and that our intents are captured in the requirements documents. To establish this certainty, we validate the requirements and verify the specification.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The customer's representatives review the information flow and the proposed functions, to confirm that they accurately reflect the customer's needs and intentions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Cleanroom software development process, proposed by IBM researchers in the mid-1980s, is designed to produce high-quality software with a high-productivity team by focusing on certifying the software with respect to specifications rather than relying on unit testing to find faults.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Their process, called cleanroom , reflects ideas used in chip production to keep faults at a minimum (Mills, Dyer, and Linger 1987). The cleanroom approach addresses two fundamental principles: to certify the software with respect to the specifications, rather than wait for unit testing to find the faults",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The principles of Cleanroom include producing zero-fault or near-zero-fault software by specifying software using box structures (black box, state box, clear box) to find omissions early, converting clear-box specifications into intended functions with correctness theorems, and applying statistical usage testing based on probability of usage to improve software reliability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The principles are applied by blending several techniques discussed in this and earlier chapters. First, software is specified using box structures, introduced in Chapter 8. The system is defined as a black box, refined as a state box, and refined again as a clear box. The box structures encourage analysts to find omissions in requirements early in the life cycle, when they are easier and cheaper to fix. Next, the clear-box specification is converted to an intended function, expressed in natural language or in mathematics, as appropriate. A correctness theorem defines a relationship, expressed as one of three correctness conditions, that describes the correctness of each intended function with respect to its control structures.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The final step involves statistical usage testing, where test cases are randomized based on probability of usage, as we saw earlier in this chapter. The results are used in a quality model to determine the expected mean time to failure and other quality measures.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Cleanroom differs from conventional testing in that it emphasizes certification against specifications and statistical usage testing rather than traditional coverage testing, which finds faults in random order. Statistical usage testing is reported to be more than 20 times as effective at extending mean time to failure (MTTF) than coverage testing.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The researchers at IBM feel that traditional coverage testing finds faults in random order, whereas statistical testing is more effective at improving overall software reliability. Cobb and Mills (1990) report that statistical usage testing is more than 20 times as effective at extending MTTF than is coverage testing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast to conventional testing, Cleanroom integrates formal specification, correctness proofs, and statistical usage testing to achieve high reliability and low fault rates, with empirical results showing an order of magnitude reduction in faults compared to traditional development.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "They claim that this is an order of magnitude reduction from the 30 to 50 faults per thousand lines of their code developed traditionally. Moreover, 'experience shows that errors left behind by correctness validation tend to be simple mistakes easily found and fixed in statistical testing, not the deep design and interface errors often encountered in traditional development' (Linger and Spangler 1992).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Ariane-5 failure was caused by software errors related to the reuse of Ariane-4 software that was not suitable for Ariane-5's requirements, specifically a software module that continued computations after lift-off which were no longer needed.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The error occurred in a software module that computed meaningful results only before lift-off. As soon as the launcher lifted off, the function performed by this module served no useful purpose, so it was no longer needed by the rest of the system. However, the module continued its computations for approximately 40 seconds of flight based on a requirement for the Ariane-4 that was not needed for Ariane-5.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Tests that might have exposed these problems include risk identification and assumption analysis tests that would have revealed differences in requirements and assumptions between Ariane-4 and Ariane-5 software.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The first stage of risk assessment is risk identification. The possible problem with reuse of the Ariane-4 software might have been identified by a decomposition of the functions; someone might have recognized early on that the requirements for Ariane-5 were different from Ariane-4. Or an assumption analysis might have revealed that the assumptions for the SRI in Ariane-4 were different from those for Ariane-5.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, more thorough reviews and test coverage, including involving nonexperts in the review process to question assumptions and formal techniques to assess test coverage completeness, might have detected the software problem.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One is to involve a nonexpert in the review process. Such a participant will question many of the assumptions that other reviewers take for granted-often wrongly. Another is to examine the completeness of test cases, either by asking an external participant to review them or by using a formal technique to assess the degree of coverage.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Simulation calculations supported by memory readouts and examination of the software itself were used to reproduce the internal events that led to the failure, indicating that simulation-based testing could have been effective in identifying the problem.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The internal events that led to the failure were reproduced by simulation calculations supported by memory readouts and examination of the software itself.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
