        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Y2K problem is an example of a maintenance problem caused by a narrow design decision, where many developers represented the year as only two characters, leading to issues when the year rolled over from 99 to 00.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The 'year 2000 problem,' where many developers represented the year as only two characters, is a good example of how simple but narrow design decisions can have a major effect on maintenance.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Section 11.3 lists several maintenance problems that relate to the Y2K issue, including technical problems such as inflexible design and inadequate design specifications, which made it difficult to modify systems to handle the new date format.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A flawed or inflexible design can require extra time for understanding, changing, and testing.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In general, inadequate design specifications and low-quality programs and documentation account for almost 10% of maintenance effort.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Staff problems such as limited understanding and the need to carefully evaluate the impact of changes on many system components also contribute to the difficulty of addressing the Y2K problem.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Parikh and Zvegintzov (1983) report that 47% of software maintenance effort is devoted to understanding the software to be modified.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "So, even a one-line change to a system component may require hundreds of tests to be sure that the change has no direct or indirect effect on another part of the system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Management priorities and morale issues also affect maintenance productivity, which can impact the ability to effectively address the Y2K problem.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Management priorities often override technical ones; managers sometimes view maintaining and enhancing as more important than building new applications.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Lientz and Swanson studies (1981) indicate that 11.9% of the problems during maintenance result from low morale and productivity.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Issues such as hardware limitations and unreliable software or data, which are also mentioned in section 11.3, may contribute to maintenance challenges but are less likely to be highlighted in popular articles about the Y2K problem.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A similar amount of effort is dedicated to hardware requirements: getting adequate storage and processing time. Problems also arise when hardware, software, or data are unreliable.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Software Engineering Laboratory (SEL) at NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center collects data from all phases of its software development projects, including failure reports where users indicate defect severity.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "D e Almeida, Lounis, and Melo (1997) used machine learning algorithms to predict costly, fault-prone software components. Using fault data collected at NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center and product measures extracted from the Ada code, they classified components as being costly or not costly to correct.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This severity information, categorized as major defect with no workaround, major defect with workaround, and cosmetic defect, can be used to classify and prioritize defects based on their impact and cost to correct.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "By analyzing these categorized failure reports, SEL can better understand which components are more fault-prone and costly to maintain, enabling more accurate maintenance effort prediction and resource allocation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "D e Almeida, Lounis, and Melo (1997) used machine learning algorithms to predict costly, fault-prone software components. Using fault data collected at NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center and product measures extracted from the Ada code, they classified components as being costly or not costly to correct.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This approach helps improve the maintenance process by focusing efforts on the most critical defects and understanding the relationship between defect severity and maintenance cost.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Maintenance research addresses a variety of problems including predicting likely sources of faults, measuring maintainability based on product information, and developing models to show interconnections among products, processes, and resources.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Many of our maintenance activities could be made easier or more effective if we were better at predicting the likely sources of faults. Researchers are looking for better ways to measure maintainability based on product information; they are developing new models to show us the interconnections among products, processes, and resources.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Research also focuses on estimating the effort needed to maintain a system and determining when it is appropriate to retire or rejuvenate legacy systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Similarly, the models will help us know how much effort is needed to maintain a system and when it is appropriate to retire a legacy system or rejuvenate it.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Another area of maintenance research is the development of tools to assist in the maintenance process, such as reengineering tools, change control and configuration management repositories, and project history databases.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Work continues on building tools to assist us in the maintenance process. Reengineering tools, change control and configuration management repositories, and project history databases are likely to become more sophisticated as researchers build prototypes based on empirical data.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Researchers are also interested in general laws of software maintenance, investigating whether software system evolution behavior is consistent and predictable.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Finally, researchers will continue to look at general laws of software maintenance, as suggested by Lehman (1980).They are eager to learn whether software engineering theory can confirm what empirical observation indicates in practice: namely, that the behavior of software systems evolution is consistent and predictable.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Key references and resources for maintenance research include journals such as IEEE Software, Communications of the ACM, and Software Maintenance: Research and Practice, as well as conferences like the International Conference on Software Maintenance.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "IEEE Software 's January 1990 issue had maintenance, reverse engineering, and design recovery as its theme; the January 1995 issue focused on legacy systems, and the January 1993 issue has a good article by Wilde, Matthews, and Huitt on the special maintenance problems of object-oriented systems. The May 1994 issue of Communications of the ACM is a special issue on reverse engineering. Software Maintenance: Research and Practice is a journal devoted entirely to maintenance issues. The International Conference on Software Maintenance is held every year, sponsored by the IEEE and ACM.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The paper by Janice Singer and Timothy Lethbridge discusses methods for studying maintenance activities by observing the work practices of software engineers engaged in maintenance projects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Researchers with the Institute for Information Technology of the National Research Council, Canada, study maintenance by observing the work practices of software engineers who are engaged in maintenance projects. A paper by Janice Singer and Timothy Lethbridge summarizes the methods they use to collect this type of data.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "From the viewpoint of a software maintainer, the data collection methods involve direct observation and possibly interaction, which could be somewhat disruptive to normal work practices but are designed to be as unobtrusive as possible to capture authentic maintenance activities.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The maintainer stands to gain by participating in such a study through the potential improvement of maintenance processes and tools, as research aims to make maintenance activities easier and more effective by better understanding the sources of faults and the effort required.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Maintenance is a ripe area of research. Many of our maintenance activities could be made easier or more effective if we were better at predicting the likely sources of faults.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Work continues on building tools to assist us in the maintenance process.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Participating in such studies also contributes to the development of models and tools that help understand the interconnections among products, processes, and resources, and assist in decision-making about maintenance effort and system rejuvenation or retirement.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
