[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The paper by Kitchenham, Pickard, and Pfleeger (1995) highlights that case studies are preferred when there is low control over variables affecting the outcome, especially in industrial environments where controlling variables can be costly or risky.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If we do not have that control, a case study is the preferred technique. But the level of control satisfies the technical concerns; we must also address practical concerns. It may be possible but very difficult to control the variables, either because of the high cost of doing so or the degree of risk involved.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Kitchenham, Pickard, and Pfleeger (1995) point out that a formal experiment is especially useful for investigating alternative methods of performing a particular selfstanding task.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "They also note that case studies are more suitable when the process changes caused by independent variables are wide-ranging and affect many dependent variables, making control and measurement difficult.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "On the other hand, a case study may be preferable to a formal experiment if the process changes caused by the independent variables are wide-ranging, requiring the effects to be measured at a high level and across too many dependent variables to control and measure.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A common pitfall in case studies is the difficulty of replication, which is often not feasible in industrial settings due to cost or practical constraints.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Another consideration is the degree to which we can replicate the basic situation we are investigating. ... If replication is not possible, then we cannot do a formal experiment.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "If a case study suffers from issues such as lack of control, difficulty in replication, or wide-ranging effects that are hard to measure, these problems may be inherent to the industrial environment and may not be fully correctable without losing feasibility.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If we have no control (i.e., the difficulty of control is high), then we should consider a case study.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, the study can still be feasible if it focuses on typical projects ('research in the typical') rather than trying to generalize broadly, and if it accepts the limitations of case study methods as described by Kitchenham, Pickard, and Pfleeger.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Case studies usually look at a typical project, rather than trying to capture information about all possible cases; these can be thought of as 'research in the typical.'",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

