[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The recognition-primed decision model describes how individuals make decisions by mentally referring to past situations stored in their memory and comparing the current situation to find a close enough match to base their decision on.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Klein has suggested a 'recognition-primed decision model,' as shown in Figure 14.6, to describe how we really make decisions. He points out that we tend to keep a repository of examples in our heads, and we draw on these situations when we are confronted with a choice. We mentally refer to a past situation and compare the current one to see if it is similar.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Applying this model directly to an organization by creating an organizational 'experience base' that describes the past work of all employees and can be searched for answers to new problems is a concept under ongoing work.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, there are several complications that must be overcome before such systems could be effective.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Some complications include",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "The context of the situation constrains understanding and options, and the problem must be well understood and represented before solving it, which can be complex at an organizational level.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The context of the situation constrains both our understanding and our options. Within that context, we must understand and represent the problem before we try to solve it.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "There is a bias in favor of estimates and decisions that can be more easily justified, which may affect the acceptance and use of organizational experience bases.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "'Legitimation' is likely to be both highly significant and somewhat overlooked in the context of software engineering. It is conceivable that estimators and decision-makers may have a preference for estimates and decisions that can be more easily justified.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Biases such as status quo bias, stereotype threat, and preference for case-specific information over statistical data can influence decision-making and estimation, complicating the use of organizational experience bases.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Other sources of bias can creep into decision-making. For example, people usually overvalue what they already own (called 'status quo bias'). Similarly, probability and payoff interact... Individuals exhibit a marked preference for case-specific, or singular, information, as opposed to general statistical, or distributional, information.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Recall is affected by recency and vividness of experience, which may cause some relevant past experiences to be discounted or overlooked in an organizational experience base.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Recall is affected by both the recency and vividness of an experience. The further into the past a factor occurred, the greater the tendency of the recaller to discount its significance.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

