    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, the context outlines categories of technology transfer inhibitors and promoters, attributes of new technologies relevant to adoption, and types of adopters, which can be used to analyze any new technology if described.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Technology transfer inhibitors and promoters fall into three categories: technological, organizational, and evidential. For example, technology transfer is inhibited by lack of packaging, by lack of relationship to a pressing technical or business problem, and by difficulty of use and understanding. By contrast, a new technology can be promoted with tools, a well-understood context, and an understanding of clear potential benefit to those on the project now or who will use the resulting product later.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- ◊ Compatibility: To what degree is the new technology consistent with existing values, past experiences, and needs of potential adopters?... - ◊ Complexity: To what degree is the new technology easy to understand and use?... - ◊ Trialability: Can the new technology be experimented with on a limited basis?... - ◊ Observability: Are the results of using the technology visible to others?",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Rogers suggests that the relevant attributes are - ◊ Relative advantage: To what degree is the new technology better than what is already available?...",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The context also describes types of adopters (innovators, early adopters, early majority, late majority) and their differing needs and perspectives on technology adoption, which align with the categories in Figure 14.1.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Innovators tend to rely on technical journals and reports from researchers and technical experts. Early adopters in turn ask the innovators to confirm a technology's credibility. Early- and late-majority members ask others in their social system, often by word of mouth or benchmarking visits.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Because early market adopters are interested in radical change, they are not as interested in the answer to this question as those in the mainstream market. That is, the early market doesn't mind restarting from the ground up, but mainstreamers are reluctant to give up that with which they are already familiar.",
